    "taxonomy": "Endostemon viscosus is classified in the following manner: it belongs to the family Lamiaceae, commonly known as the mint family. This species is further classified as belonging to the genus Endostemon, which is native to the tropical regions of Africa and Madagascar. The genus Endostemon is closely related to other genera in the same family, such as Pogostemon and Siphomeria. Endostemon viscosus is a perennial herb that is known for its sticky leaves and stems. It is a relatively understudied species within the Lamiaceae family, with limited information available on its classification and characteristics.",
    "benefits": "Endostemon viscosus has been traditionally used in various cultures for its medicinal properties. It is believed to have anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial effects, which may help in treating wounds and skin infections. Some studies suggest that the plant may also have antioxidant and antidiabetic properties, making it a potential natural remedy for managing blood sugar levels. Furthermore, Endostemon viscosus is thought to have immunomodulatory effects, which could aid in boosting the immune system and preventing illnesses. However, more research is needed to fully understand the health benefits of Endostemon viscosus and to confirm its efficacy in treating various health conditions.",
